      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase leading-tight mb-8">
        Magnetic Conveyors
      </h1>
      <div class="text-xl text-ink-muted leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        <p>A magnetic conveyor uses permanent magnets or electromagnets beneath the conveying surface to hold and transport ferrous metal products , steel cans, tin-plated lids, bottle caps, and sheet metal stampings. The magnetic field passes through a non-magnetic slider bed to grip ferrous items securely, allowing transport along flat, inclined, vertical, and even inverted paths without mechanical clamps or fixtures. Magnetic conveyors are standard equipment on <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/beverage/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">beverage canning lines</a>, cap feeding systems, and metal stamping operations where ferrous parts must move reliably at high speeds or through orientation changes.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- How Magnetic Conveyors Work -->
  <article class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="how-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Fundamentals</div>
      <h2 id="how-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        How Magnetic Conveyors <span class="text-accent">Work</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>Magnetic conveyors exploit the attraction between a magnetic field and ferrous (iron-containing) materials. Permanent magnets or electromagnets mount beneath, beside, or above a non-magnetic conveyor surface , typically stainless steel sheet, UHMW polyethylene, or aluminum plate. The magnetic flux passes through this non-magnetic barrier and acts on any ferrous product placed on or near the conveyor surface. The product adheres to the surface with a force proportional to the magnet strength, the air gap (slider bed thickness), and the ferrous content of the product.</p>

        <p>The conveyor belt or chain rides over the magnetic slider bed, carrying products along the conveyor path. Products remain magnetically held to the belt surface throughout travel , including inclines, declines, curves, and inverted sections. The belt material must be non-magnetic (typically polyester, polyurethane, or silicone) so it does not interfere with the magnetic field reaching the product. At the discharge point, the belt separates from the magnet assembly, and the magnetic hold releases. Products drop onto downstream conveyors or into containers at the discharge end.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Permanent Magnets vs. Electromagnets</h3>
        <p>Permanent-magnet systems use ceramic ferrite or rare-earth neodymium magnets arranged in rows or strips beneath the slider bed. Ferrite magnets are the standard choice for light products (cans, lids, caps under 200 grams) and provide reliable holding force at low cost. Neodymium rare-earth magnets deliver 5-10 times the flux density of ferrite magnets per unit volume, enabling stronger holding for heavier parts, thicker slider beds, or higher speeds. Permanent magnets require no power, generate no heat, and maintain their strength for decades under normal operating temperatures.</p>

        <p>Electromagnet systems use electric coils to generate the magnetic field. They offer adjustable field strength , operators increase or decrease current to match different product weights or materials. Electromagnets also allow instant on/off control, useful for releasing products at specific positions along the conveyor. The drawbacks are power consumption, heat generation (requiring cooling in continuous operation), and higher complexity. Electromagnet conveyors cost $$$ compared to $ for permanent-magnet systems. Most packaging applications use permanent magnets because the product type and weight remain consistent.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Magnetic Field Geometry</h3>
        <p>The arrangement of magnets beneath the slider bed determines the field pattern and holding characteristics. Alternating-pole arrangements (north-south-north-south across the conveyor width) create a dense, short-range field ideal for thin products like can lids and closures. Same-pole arrangements produce a deeper field that penetrates thicker slider beds and holds heavier products but with less surface uniformity. Halbach arrays , a specialized alternating arrangement , concentrate nearly all magnetic flux on one side of the array, maximizing holding force on the product side while minimizing stray fields on the back side. Magnetic <a href="/resources/conveyor-suppliers/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor suppliers</a> engineer the magnet layout for each application based on product weight, material thickness, and conveyor geometry.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: Bunting Magnetics headquarters in Newton, Kansas -->
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- Types of Magnetic Conveyors -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="types-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">System Types</div>
      <h2 id="types-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Types of <span class="text-accent">Magnetic Conveyors</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Under-Belt Magnetic Conveyors</h3>
        <p>Under-belt magnetic conveyors are the most common type. Magnets mount beneath a <a href="/conveyor-types/flat-belt-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">flat belt conveyor</a> slider bed in a fixed channel or adjustable-height tray. The belt runs on top of the slider bed as a standard flat belt conveyor. Products placed on the belt experience magnetic attraction that holds them firmly against the belt surface. Under-belt systems transport products horizontally, up inclines, and down declines. The magnetic hold prevents products from sliding back on <a href="/conveyor-types/incline-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">incline conveyors</a> and prevents products from tumbling or accelerating on declines.</p>

        <p>Under-belt magnetic conveyors on beverage lines transport steel cans at speeds of 1,000-2,000 cans per minute in single file. The magnets hold the lightweight empty cans (12-15 grams for a standard 12-oz steel can body) firmly enough to prevent them from tipping, bouncing, or blowing off the belt at high speeds. Without magnetic hold, empty steel cans at these speeds are unstable and blow off conventional belt conveyors due to aerodynamic effects from adjacent high-speed cans and ambient air currents in the plant.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Overhead Magnetic Conveyors</h3>
        <p>Overhead magnetic conveyors suspend ferrous products from below, transporting them along an elevated path above the production floor. The magnets mount above the conveyor surface so the magnetic field pulls products upward against the belt or slider. Products hang from the conveying surface, held by magnetic force against gravity. Overhead magnetic conveyors carry steel cans, lids, and parts above process equipment, between mezzanine levels, and over operator work areas where floor-level conveyors would obstruct access.</p>

        <p>Overhead systems require stronger magnets than under-belt systems because the magnets must overcome the full weight of the product (pulling up against gravity) rather than merely stabilizing the product on a horizontal surface. Neodymium rare-earth magnets are standard for overhead magnetic conveyors. The slider bed thickness must be minimized to reduce the air gap between the magnets and the product, maximizing the available holding force. Safety requirements mandate catch trays or secondary containment below overhead magnetic conveyors in case products release unexpectedly , due to a non-ferrous product mixed in, a magnet failure, or a product heavier than the magnet design load.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Side-Grip Magnetic Conveyors</h3>
        <p>Side-grip magnetic conveyors hold products by their sides rather than their top or bottom surface. Two parallel magnetic rails grip the sides of cylindrical ferrous products (cans, tubes, cartridges) and transport them horizontally or vertically. The product floats between the two magnetic fields without contacting a belt or slider bed on its top or bottom. Side-grip systems work for products that cannot be conveyed on their top or bottom , wet cans with fresh coatings, cans with labels that cannot be scratched, or products with adhesive on their bottom surface.</p>

        <p>Side-grip magnetic conveyors also serve as can elevators, lifting steel cans vertically between floor levels. The two magnetic rails grip opposite sides of the can body and the chain or belt between the rails carries the cans upward. At the top, the rails diverge and the cans release onto a downstream <a href="/conveyor-functions/infeed-outfeed/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">infeed conveyor</a>. Side-grip elevators occupy a minimal footprint compared to incline conveyors and handle the lightweight empty cans gently without denting or deforming them.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Magnetic Cap Elevators and Feeders</h3>
        <p>Cap elevators use magnetic conveyors to transport steel or tin-plated closures from bulk hoppers up to cap sorting and feeding equipment. A magnetic belt conveyor reaches into a hopper of loose caps, and the magnetic field grabs caps from the pile. The belt carries the caps up an incline and discharges them onto a cap sorter or orientor. This bulk cap feeding method replaces vibratory bowl feeders for high-speed lines because it handles higher volumes with less noise and less cap damage. Specialty closure-handling OEMs build magnetic cap elevator systems sized for specific cap diameters, weights, and line speeds on beverage and food packaging lines.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Tin Can and Beverage Applications -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="cans-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Can Line Applications</div>
      <h2 id="cans-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Tin Can and <span class="text-accent">Beverage Line</span> Applications
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">Empty can transport:</strong> Empty steel cans weigh as little as 12-20 grams and are extremely unstable on conventional conveyors at production speeds. Magnetic conveyors hold empty cans firmly on the belt surface, preventing tipping, bouncing, and blow-offs. Can making plants use magnetic conveyors extensively to move empty can bodies between forming, trimming, washing, coating, printing, and necking operations. Speeds of 1,500-2,500 cans per minute in single-file are standard on magnetic can conveyors.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Lid and end transport:</strong> Steel can ends (lids) are flat, lightweight, and extremely prone to sticking together due to surface tension and static. Magnetic conveyors transport stacks of can ends in controlled columns and transport individual ends in single layers to seaming machines. The magnetic hold keeps individual ends flat against the belt, preventing them from flipping, overlapping, or jamming at transfer points.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Inverted can transport:</strong> Some can processing steps require inverted cans (open end down). Magnetic conveyors transport inverted cans on overhead sections where the cans hang from the belt by magnetic force. The can bodies drain, dry, or cool while traveling inverted. At the end of the inverted section, the conveyor transitions back to upright and deposits the cans right-side-up onto downstream equipment.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Can twists and spirals:</strong> Magnetic conveyors navigate twisted and spiral paths to change can elevation or orientation in <a href="/conveyor-types/serpentine-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">beverage line applications</a>. A magnetic twist conveyor rotates the conveying surface 90 or 180 degrees along the conveyor length, reorienting cans as they travel. Magnetic spiral conveyors carry cans up or down in a helical path with a compact footprint. The magnetic hold prevents cans from sliding or falling off the tilted conveyor surface through the twist or spiral.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Multi-lane can conveying:</strong> High-speed <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/beverage/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">beverage lines</a> running 1,500+ cans per minute use multi-lane magnetic conveyors with 4-8 parallel lanes on a single wide belt. Lane dividers separate the cans into parallel streams. The magnetic field holds cans in all lanes simultaneously. Multi-lane magnetic conveyors reduce the number of conveyor frames and drives needed compared to separate single-lane conveyors for each stream.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Industrial and Automotive Applications -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="industrial-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Industrial Applications</div>
      <h2 id="industrial-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Industrial and <span class="text-accent">Automotive Applications</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">Metal stamping and press operations:</strong> Magnetic conveyors remove stamped steel parts from press beds and transport them to inspection, deburring, or assembly stations. The magnetic hold grips parts immediately as they exit the press die, preventing parts from stacking, overlapping, or falling between the press and the conveyor. Stamped parts often have oil residue on their surfaces, making friction-based conveying unreliable. Magnetic hold is independent of surface friction, so oily parts transport as reliably as clean parts.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Automotive body panel transport:</strong> <a href="/industries/automotive-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Automotive manufacturing</a> uses magnetic conveyors to move steel sheet metal blanks and stamped body panels between press lines, welding cells, and coating stations. Large magnetic slider beds hold heavy steel blanks (5-50 kg) flat during transport, preventing warping or deformation from unsupported sagging. The magnetic conveyors integrate with robotic pick-and-place systems that load and unload panels from the conveyor at each processing station.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Chip and scrap conveyors:</strong> Magnetic conveyors collect and transport steel chips, turnings, and scrap from machining centers, lathes, and CNC mills. A magnetic belt conveyor runs beneath the machining area, collecting ferrous chips that fall from the cutting operation. The magnetic field holds chips against the belt even when mixed with cutting fluid. At the discharge end, the belt separates from the magnet assembly and the chips fall into a scrap bin or briquetting press. These chip conveyors keep machine shop floors clean and recover valuable scrap metal automatically.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Magnetic separation conveyors:</strong> Magnetic conveyors separate ferrous materials from non-ferrous materials in recycling, mining, and food processing. A magnetic drum or magnetic head pulley at the conveyor discharge holds ferrous items on the belt past the normal discharge point while non-ferrous materials fall off at the standard trajectory. The ferrous materials release when the belt moves past the magnetic zone, falling into a separate collection bin. This passive separation process requires no sensors, controls, or compressed air , the magnetic field alone performs the sorting.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Medical device and electronics assembly:</strong> Small magnetic conveyors transport steel components, spring clips, fasteners, and ferritic stainless steel parts through assembly and inspection processes. The magnetic hold prevents tiny parts from vibrating off the conveyor, falling into gaps, or being displaced by air currents from clean room HVAC systems. Precision positioning on magnetic conveyors allows <a href="/conveyor-functions/inspection-detection/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">vision inspection systems</a> to image each part in a known position and orientation.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Design and Selection -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="selection-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Selection Guide</div>
      <h2 id="selection-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Design and <span class="text-accent">Selection Criteria</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">Confirm the product is ferrous.</strong> Magnetic conveyors work only with ferrous materials , steel, iron, tin-plate, and ferritic stainless steels. Aluminum, brass, copper, austenitic stainless steel (304, 316), plastic, and glass are non-ferrous and are not attracted by permanent magnets. Test the product with a magnet before specifying a magnetic conveyor. Some products appear metallic but contain no ferrous material (aluminum cans, brass fittings, zinc die-cast parts).</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Calculate the required holding force.</strong> The magnetic system must hold the product against all forces that act on it: gravity (on inclines, overhead, and inverted sections), centrifugal force (on curves), inertia (during acceleration, deceleration, and direction changes), and aerodynamic drag (from ambient air and adjacent high-speed products). The required holding force equals the product weight multiplied by a safety factor (typically 2-3x for horizontal conveyors, 4-5x for overhead and inverted sections). Magnet suppliers provide pull-force ratings at specified air gaps.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Specify the slider bed material and thickness.</strong> The slider bed separates the product from the magnets and determines the air gap. Thinner slider beds provide stronger holding force but wear faster. UHMW polyethylene slider beds offer low friction and good wear resistance for most packaging applications. Stainless steel slider beds provide superior wear resistance and washdown capability for food and beverage applications. The slider bed material must be non-magnetic , avoid carbon steel or ferritic stainless for the slider bed, as these materials absorb the magnetic flux and prevent it from reaching the product.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Match belt material to the application.</strong> The conveyor belt must be non-magnetic and compatible with the product and environment. Polyurethane belts suit general industrial applications. FDA-approved belts are required for food and beverage can conveying. Silicone belts handle high-temperature applications (oven-dried coatings on cans). The belt thickness adds to the effective air gap, so thinner belts provide stronger holding force.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Consider speed and throughput.</strong> Magnetic conveyors operate at speeds from 10 FPM (precision assembly applications) to 600+ FPM (high-speed can lines). Higher speeds require stronger magnetic hold because aerodynamic forces increase with the square of speed. Products transitioning from magnetic to non-magnetic conveyor sections at high speed can become unstable when the magnetic hold suddenly releases , use gradual magnetic field taper at discharge points for high-speed applications.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Evaluate cost relative to alternatives.</strong> Under-belt magnetic conveyors with ferrite magnets cost $ , comparable to standard <a href="/conveyor-types/flat-belt-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">flat belt conveyors</a> with a modest premium for the magnet assembly. Overhead magnetic systems cost $$ due to stronger magnets, structural support requirements, and safety containment. Electromagnet systems cost $$$ due to power supplies, controls, and cooling. For horizontal transport of ferrous products, magnetic conveyors compete with standard belt and roller conveyors. The magnetic option wins when product stability at high speed, incline transport without cleats, or inverted transport justifies the additional cost.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Maintenance -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="maint-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Maintenance</div>
      <h2 id="maint-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Maintenance and <span class="text-accent">Troubleshooting</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">Slider bed wear:</strong> The slider bed is the primary wear item on magnetic conveyors. Ferrous products press harder against the slider bed surface than non-magnetic products because magnetic attraction adds to the contact force. This increased contact force accelerates slider bed wear, especially on incline and overhead sections where the product weight and magnetic holding force combine against the slider surface. Inspect slider beds monthly on high-speed can lines and replace them when wear reduces the bed thickness below the manufacturer's minimum specification.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Belt tracking:</strong> Magnetic conveyors create asymmetric lateral forces on the belt when products are not centered on the conveyor width. These lateral forces can cause belt mistracking. Ensure products feed onto the magnetic conveyor centered on the belt width. Use belt tracking rollers and guides as on standard belt conveyors, but verify that tracking hardware is non-magnetic (stainless steel or aluminum, not carbon steel).</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Product release issues:</strong> Products that do not release cleanly at the conveyor discharge point indicate excessive magnetic hold or insufficient belt speed at the discharge. The belt must carry the product past the end of the magnet assembly and around the head pulley before the product discharges. If the magnet assembly extends too close to the head pulley, the magnetic field holds products past the intended discharge point. Adjustable magnet assemblies allow fine-tuning the release point.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Magnet degradation:</strong> Permanent magnets lose strength when exposed to temperatures above their rated maximum (typically 80°C for ferrite, 80-200°C for various neodymium grades) or when subjected to strong demagnetizing fields. In normal packaging environments at ambient temperature, permanent magnets maintain their strength indefinitely. High-temperature conveyor applications (post-oven can cooling) require high-temperature-rated magnet grades , specify the maximum operating temperature when ordering.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h2 id="faq-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-10">
        Frequently Asked <span class="text-accent">Questions</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8" open>
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is a magnetic conveyor?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>A magnetic conveyor uses permanent magnets or electromagnets beneath the conveying surface to hold and transport ferrous metal products , steel cans, lids, caps, and sheet metal parts. The magnetic field grips products through a non-magnetic slider bed, allowing transport on flat, inclined, vertical, and inverted paths. See our <a href="/conveyor-types/flat-belt-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">flat belt conveyor guide</a> for the base belt technology used in most magnetic systems.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            Can magnetic conveyors handle aluminum cans?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>Standard permanent-magnet conveyors cannot hold aluminum because aluminum is non-ferrous. Aluminum cans require eddy-current systems or alternative conveying methods like air conveyors or mass-flow <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/beverage/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">beverage conveyors</a>. Magnetic conveyors suit steel (tin-plate) cans only.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            How strong do the magnets need to be?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>Magnet strength depends on the product weight, conveyor orientation, and speed. Ceramic ferrite magnets suit light products under 200 grams on horizontal and <a href="/conveyor-types/incline-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">incline conveyors</a>. Rare-earth neodymium magnets provide 5-10 times more holding force for heavier parts, overhead sections, or high-speed applications. The slider bed thickness also affects the effective magnetic force reaching the product.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What maintenance do magnetic conveyors require?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>Permanent magnets require no maintenance and last indefinitely under normal temperatures. Focus maintenance on slider bed wear (inspect monthly on high-speed lines), belt tracking, belt replacement, and drive components. Electromagnet systems also need power supply, wiring, and cooling system maintenance. Slider beds wear faster on magnetic conveyors than standard conveyors because magnetic attraction increases contact force.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

